start in layers  for webserver troubleshooting

Client
 ↓
DNS
 ↓
Network / Firewall
 ↓
Port listening
 ↓
Web server (Nginx / Caddy / Apache)
 ↓
Reverse proxy
 ↓
Backend application
 ↓
Database / dependencies


Step 1 — Check if the service is listening
First question:
Is anything listening on the port?
ss -tulnp

Step 2 — Check the web server itself

Verify the service.
systemctl status nginx
systemctl status apache2
systemctl status caddy

Step 4 — Check firewall rules


Many problems come from firewall.
Check:
iptables -L -n


Step 5 — Check reverse proxy configuration
Many modern setups use:
Caddy
Nginx
Traefik

They often proxy to another service.
Example from your case:
Caddy :80
↓
reverse_proxy localhost:5050
So test the backend directly:
curl localhost:5050

Step 7 — Check dependencies

Many apps depend on:
database
Redis
external APIs

Backend → PostgreSQL
So check DB:
pg_lsclusters
systemctl status postgresql

Step 8 — Check port mismatches

A very common issue.
Example:
App expects 5433
DB running on 5432

This caused your issue.
Fix via:
config change
port fowarding
service reconfiguration

tep 9 — Check network flow

Sometimes use:


curl -v http://127.0.0.1
This shows:
connection
headers
errors